            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 8,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1501225653,
            "creation_date": 1500971719,
            "body": "<p>The method reference passed for <code>combiner<\/code> does not really fit.\nTry:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>List&lt;String&gt; namesAsList = names\n  .collect(ArrayList::new, List::add, List::addAll);\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>You passed the <code>List::add<\/code> and compiler is doing its best to try to interpret it as a combiner instance of <code>BiConsumer<\/code> type. Hence, the weird argument mismatch error.<\/p>\n\n<hr>\n\n<p>Also, I assume you are implementing this only for research purposes. If you want to collect a <code>Stream<\/code> to a <code>List<\/code>, you can simply use:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>.collect(Collectors.toList());\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>If you want to collect you <code>Stream<\/code> to <code>ArrayList<\/code> specifically, you can go for:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>.collect(Collectors.toCollection(ArrayList::new));\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 45297996,
            "question_id": 45297901,
            "last_edit_date": 1501225653
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/W6OMC.png?s=256",
                "account_id": 1056871,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 1059372,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1059372/eugene",
                "reputation": 121845,
                "display_name": "Eugene",
                "accept_rate": 97
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 6,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1500972103,
            "creation_date": 1500971826,
            "body": "<p>The problem is in the <code>combiner<\/code>, specifically: <code>List::add<\/code> should really be <code>List::addAll<\/code>.<\/p>\n\n<p>Or more readable like this:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>List&lt;String&gt; namesAsList = names.collect(\n            () -&gt; new ArrayList&lt;&gt;(), \n            List::add, \n            List::addAll);\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>You can re-write that with lambda expression when you are un-sure btw:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>List&lt;String&gt; namesAsList = names.collect(\n            () -&gt; new ArrayList&lt;&gt;(),\n            List::add,\n            (List&lt;String&gt; left, List&lt;String&gt; right) -&gt; {\n                left.addAll(right);\n            });\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Notice that there are other problems as-well, like <code>() -&gt; new ArrayList&lt;String&gt;()<\/code>, the type will be inferred by the compiler here, so no need for a <code>&lt;String&gt;<\/code>, like this: <code>() -&gt; new ArrayList&lt;&gt;()<\/code>. Also this can be transformed to a method reference too: <code>ArrayList::new<\/code>, so ultimately it would be even simpler:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code> List&lt;String&gt; namesAsList = names.collect(\n            ArrayList::new,\n            List::add,\n            List::addAll);\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>This btw is the same thing that <code>Collectors.toList<\/code> does internally, so even further this can be simplified to:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>List&lt;String&gt; namesAsList = names.collect(Collectors.toList());\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>The only problem is that the specification is free to change that (to return any <em>other<\/em>  <code>List<\/code> besides <code>ArrayList<\/code>), so it could be written:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code> List&lt;String&gt; namesAsList = names.collect(Collectors.toCollection(ArrayList::new));\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 45298038,
            "question_id": 45297901,
            "last_edit_date": 1500972103
        }
